The paper presents a new algorithm for discovering patterns in time series and sequential data, which involves building a minimal set of hidden, Markovian states that can produce the observed behavior. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories, as the algorithm involves inferring the causal architecture of the underlying process from the data. Additionally, the paper discusses the predictive optimality properties of the inferred causal states, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the statistics (cs.ST) and information theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category, as it deals with sequential data and patterns in behavior.
